1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:01,650 --> 00:00:03,050
Sure, Mom, we're fine.

3
00:00:03,550 --> 00:00:05,050
The storm pretty much missed us.

4
00:00:06,050 --> 00:00:07,550
And did you excuse me at school?

5
00:00:08,550 --> 00:00:12,220
Wow, meningitis with suspected mononucleosis.

6
00:00:12,220 --> 00:00:13,880
Wow, Mom, you're really great, thanks.

7
00:00:14,850 --> 00:00:17,940
Yeah, we're opening soon, we're second in line.

8
00:00:17,940 --> 00:00:18,640
Bye then.

9
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:32,850
How many?

10
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:35,750
Give me everything you've got.

11
00:00:41,050 --> 00:00:42,050
No way, that's it!

12
00:00:42,650 --> 00:00:43,050
That's it!

13
00:01:19,650 --> 00:01:20,650
So, where are we headed?

14
00:01:20,850 --> 00:01:22,550
Don't even ask, Mr. Pacovsky.

15
00:01:23,050 --> 00:01:23,950
It's sold out.

16
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:29,140
Damn it.

17
00:01:33,450 --> 00:01:34,650
Mom will hug you.

18
00:01:35,150 --> 00:01:35,550
Really?

19
00:01:35,750 --> 00:01:37,150
Yesterday she told me to get lost.

20
00:01:37,150 --> 00:01:38,910
Yeah well, you have to promise her something in return.

21
00:01:39,090 --> 00:01:40,350
Like, that you'll do the dishes or something.

22
00:01:40,630 --> 00:01:41,010
Ah.

23
00:01:41,670 --> 00:01:42,310
See you later.

24
00:01:43,950 --> 00:01:45,850
What happened to you, Mr. Ozzak?

25
00:01:45,890 --> 00:01:48,250
They came with Tonya and still wanted to go to the concert.

26
00:01:48,250 --> 00:01:52,250
Come on, Ozzak, don't worry about Tonya, you've already seen the Stones anyway.

27
00:01:52,550 --> 00:01:54,110
Every one of their concerts is unique.

28
00:01:54,450 --> 00:01:55,890
That's just because they forget the lyrics.

29
00:01:55,890 --> 00:01:58,310
And besides, this is definitely their last tour.

30
00:01:58,370 --> 00:02:00,170
But they said that the last time and the time before.

31
00:02:01,050 --> 00:02:02,650
This one is guaranteed to be the last.

32
00:02:02,950 --> 00:02:06,290
Ozzak, I'll show you something that'll definitely cheer you up.

33
00:02:06,550 --> 00:02:10,750
I've got something much better here than tickets to one Rolling Stones concert.

34
00:02:10,750 --> 00:02:12,650
You have tickets to all the concerts?

35
00:02:13,310 --> 00:02:14,250
Even better.

36
00:02:14,430 --> 00:02:15,390
Nothing better exists.

37
00:02:15,850 --> 00:02:16,550
Voila, Scrabble.

38
00:02:19,540 --> 00:02:20,660
I don't know this band.

39
00:02:20,900 --> 00:02:21,940
What is it, Marcelka?

40
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:23,100
You don't know it, Tomas?

41
00:02:23,160 --> 00:02:23,840
An amazing game.

42
00:02:23,940 --> 00:02:25,040
Yeah, but I know it.

43
00:02:25,260 --> 00:02:26,400
We played it on a ski trip.

44
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:30,140
And I had totally crappy letters, but in the end I managed to spell "somersault."

45
00:02:30,240 --> 00:02:31,220
And I won.

46
00:02:31,480 --> 00:02:33,380
Well, I applaud the somersault.

47
00:02:33,600 --> 00:02:35,700
I recently managed "masturbation."

48
00:02:36,700 --> 00:02:38,740
Well, how does that compare to my somersault?

49
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:41,260
I think masturbation is way easier.

50
00:02:41,500 --> 00:02:43,600
Yeah, so try it then, if you're so smart.

51
00:02:43,780 --> 00:02:44,660
In front of you? No way.

52
00:02:44,660 --> 00:02:46,750
I'd rather do the somersault.

53
00:02:47,020 --> 00:02:47,820
And who do you play with?

54
00:02:47,820 --> 00:02:51,680
A week ago I became a member of the Czech Scrabble Association.

55
00:02:52,750 --> 00:02:54,080
But if you want to play?

56
00:02:54,250 --> 00:02:55,450
Well, probably not.

57
00:02:55,750 --> 00:02:56,350
I understand.

58
00:02:56,650 --> 00:02:57,650
You're afraid of losing.

59
00:02:58,050 --> 00:02:58,660
Excuse me.

60
00:02:58,660 --> 00:03:00,240
You've forgotten about my somersault.

61
00:03:00,400 --> 00:03:03,600
Your somersault and my masturbation can't even be compared.

62
00:03:03,640 --> 00:03:04,980
And what's harder about masturbation?

63
00:03:05,100 --> 00:03:06,000
Let's settle this then.

64
00:03:06,160 --> 00:03:07,560
Fine, tonight at our place.

65
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:09,660
But at least three of us, otherwise I won't enjoy it.

66
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:09,980
Dad?

67
00:03:10,100 --> 00:03:12,120
Well sure, why not?

68
00:03:20,580 --> 00:03:21,020
Ozzak?

69
00:03:21,850 --> 00:03:24,150
Don't you want to play with us after all?

70
00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:27,690
Rockers don't play kiddie games.

71
00:03:28,150 --> 00:03:30,050
Yeah, and I'm here.

72
00:03:30,650 --> 00:03:34,450
"Cyst," and I add "poli," and that makes "policeman."

73
00:03:34,750 --> 00:03:41,650
Ozzak, "cyst," as in a closed pathological cavity of various origin and content, is spelled with a Y.

74
00:03:42,850 --> 00:03:45,250
Whereas "policeman" is spelled with a soft I.

75
00:03:45,780 --> 00:03:48,360
You don't know this cop who's really tough.

76
00:03:48,540 --> 00:03:51,360
In Guts she's right, a "policeman" with a hard I is no policeman at all.

77
00:03:51,580 --> 00:03:52,600
So go tell him that!

78
00:03:53,350 --> 00:03:53,940
What's wrong with him?

79
00:03:53,940 --> 00:03:55,640
Tell his kids that, tell his wife!

80
00:03:57,150 --> 00:04:01,220
No, Ozzak, this game has rules and we have to follow them.

81
00:04:01,350 --> 00:04:02,350
What is that?

82
00:04:02,350 --> 00:04:05,340
The International Scrabble Association dictionary.

83
00:04:05,340 --> 00:04:07,140
Every word in the world is in there.

84
00:04:07,750 --> 00:04:14,650
And I'm putting X next to U, which gives us KSU.

85
00:04:14,850 --> 00:04:18,940
For triple points, so that's thirty-three points.

86
00:04:18,940 --> 00:04:19,760
And what's ksu?

87
00:04:19,940 --> 00:04:21,240
Ksu is nothing, she's cheating.

88
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:24,950
Ksu is a Vietnamese coin.

89
00:04:25,550 --> 00:04:26,750
Here, please.

90
00:04:27,260 --> 00:04:28,200
Really?

91
00:04:29,050 --> 00:04:32,100
The fact is, bro, is Marcelka playing by the rules?

92
00:04:32,100 --> 00:04:33,980
Rules are meant to be broken.

93
00:04:34,060 --> 00:04:35,420
And I'll put here.

94
00:04:36,450 --> 00:04:38,050
Chair.

95
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:38,960
Chair.

96
00:04:39,550 --> 00:04:40,100
And "chair" is...

97
00:04:40,100 --> 00:04:41,320
"Chair" doesn't exist.

98
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:42,560
Oh.

99
00:04:43,720 --> 00:04:44,720
And what am I sitting on?

100
00:04:44,900 --> 00:04:46,180
"Chair" isn't in the dictionary.

101
00:04:47,050 --> 00:04:48,750
Oh, what's this then?

102
00:04:49,250 --> 00:04:51,550
That's "chidle," Ozzak is missing an R.

103
00:04:51,900 --> 00:04:53,780
Wait, that must be some kind of printing error.

104
00:04:54,020 --> 00:04:55,780
What's written is final.

105
00:04:57,250 --> 00:04:59,750
We play by the rules, right bro?

106
00:05:00,550 --> 00:05:02,310
But the rest of us will finish the game, right?

107
00:05:04,350 --> 00:05:06,250
I win, by forfeit.

108
00:05:07,340 --> 00:05:10,020
You simply can't handle losing, Mr. Ozzak!

109
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:10,740
That's right.

110
00:05:11,420 --> 00:05:13,240
I can handle it perfectly well, actually.

111
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:15,360
And if I wanted to, I would have lost a long time ago.

112
00:05:26,650 --> 00:05:28,180
I have two pieces of news for you, Mr. Ozzak.

113
00:05:28,450 --> 00:05:32,750
The good one is, if we pull it off, we'll come out right in Mick Jagger's dressing room.

114
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:34,780
Super, Bejk.

115
00:05:35,340 --> 00:05:36,240
And the bad one?

116
00:05:36,950 --> 00:05:38,350
That we won't pull it off.

117
00:05:38,650 --> 00:05:42,750
There is a passageway through the sewers, but our chances are almost zero.

118
00:05:43,350 --> 00:05:47,010
What kind of problem could there be that the two of us couldn't solve?

119
00:05:47,250 --> 00:05:49,050
It's completely flooded with water.

120
00:05:50,850 --> 00:05:52,350
I can dive, my boy.

121
00:05:52,650 --> 00:05:55,750
At the lake I lasted five minutes underwater before they fished me out.

122
00:05:57,200 --> 00:05:57,920
What am I?

123
00:05:58,380 --> 00:05:58,940
Fat.

124
00:05:59,000 --> 00:05:59,440
What?

125
00:06:00,140 --> 00:06:01,220
Cool, but fat.

126
00:06:01,950 --> 00:06:03,440
That passageway is only 25 centimeters wide.

127
00:06:03,750 --> 00:06:05,520
Ah, well look.

128
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:06,060
Yeah!

129
00:06:07,250 --> 00:06:09,850
We'll drill through here with a jackhammer and that's it.

130
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:10,960
Wow!

131
00:06:12,050 --> 00:06:15,250
You think if we drill through like crazy they won't notice us?

132
00:06:19,450 --> 00:06:22,850
You wouldn't believe what happened to me today.

133
00:06:22,950 --> 00:06:28,240
Zoran got three tickets to Rolling Stones from a sponsor.

134
00:06:28,240 --> 00:06:33,180
My husband isn't exactly a big fan of Rolling Stones, so he wanted to throw the tickets away.

135
00:06:33,280 --> 00:06:37,520
And I told him, darling, if you don't want those tickets, I'll gladly take them.

136
00:06:37,850 --> 00:06:44,350
So I, I now have three tickets to Rolling Stones.

137
00:06:45,090 --> 00:06:47,410
Everyone who's anyone will be at the concert.

138
00:06:47,490 --> 00:06:50,630
So I'll go too, even though the music means nothing to me.

139
00:06:50,930 --> 00:06:55,830
And now, Tomas, tell me what I should do with the remaining two tickets.

140
00:06:56,310 --> 00:06:58,410
Would you know of anyone who'd want them?

141
00:06:58,490 --> 00:07:00,850
Me, me, me, me, here, here, I want them.

142
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:09,280
If anyone comes to mind, Tomas, please tell them that the tickets go to whoever beats me at Scrabble.

143
00:07:09,500 --> 00:07:10,580
I'll play against you.

144
00:07:11,750 --> 00:07:14,020
Ozzak, you're here too?

145
00:07:14,850 --> 00:07:16,050
What were you saying?

146
00:07:16,540 --> 00:07:18,100
I want to beat you at Scrabble.

147
00:07:19,120 --> 00:07:21,420
That's an amusing thought.

148
00:07:21,840 --> 00:07:23,340
Tomas and Iva will play too.

149
00:07:23,650 --> 00:07:29,150
Why? Bro, yesterday we had to swear to you that we'd never touch those stupid letters again.

150
00:07:33,650 --> 00:07:37,150
Scrabble is an excellent social game that develops the mind.

151
00:07:37,750 --> 00:07:46,710
And I'm asking you not to say such ugly words like "stupid letters" here in front of Marcelka.

152
00:07:46,710 --> 00:07:50,430
So the rule about whoever says the word "ksu" sleeps at the train station is no longer in effect?

153
00:07:50,950 --> 00:07:52,450
Bro, don't be a pain.

154
00:08:03,150 --> 00:08:04,350
Ozzak, get up.

155
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:05,720
Is it morning already?

156
00:08:05,820 --> 00:08:06,860
No, it's already noon.

157
00:08:07,280 --> 00:08:10,240
You missed the morning shift at the shop, you're going to practice Scrabble.

158
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:11,340
I am practicing.

159
00:08:11,740 --> 00:08:14,540
You think you'll learn it by sleeping on it?

160
00:08:14,680 --> 00:08:15,820
It worked for me at school.

161
00:08:15,860 --> 00:08:16,980
You didn't even finish school.

162
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:17,560
Because I'm dumb.

163
00:08:18,070 --> 00:08:20,070
Have you ever tried stuffing an entire globe under your pillow?

164
00:08:20,490 --> 00:08:22,790
So that's really your only training method?

165
00:08:22,970 --> 00:08:23,610
Of course not.

166
00:08:24,250 --> 00:08:27,230
For lunch I made myself alphabet soup.

167
00:08:27,250 --> 00:08:32,050
Sorry for briefly thinking that sleeping on the dictionary was the stupidest study method.

168
00:08:32,050 --> 00:08:33,890
I actually know way more words than yesterday.

169
00:08:33,970 --> 00:08:35,370
Yeah, alright, show me.

170
00:08:36,850 --> 00:08:40,750
C-V-N-X-C-V.

171
00:08:43,950 --> 00:08:46,950
For God's sake, bro, what did you make that alphabet soup from?

172
00:08:49,250 --> 00:08:50,250
Well, that's great.

173
00:08:50,550 --> 00:08:52,350
And how do you plan to play Scrabble tomorrow?

174
00:08:52,850 --> 00:08:54,450
You can make a word even with four letters.

175
00:08:54,450 --> 00:08:54,890
Yeah?

176
00:08:55,230 --> 00:08:55,450
Yep.

177
00:08:56,150 --> 00:08:56,950
Watch this.

178
00:09:02,850 --> 00:09:03,750
And there you go.

179
00:09:08,650 --> 00:09:11,050
Wait, these letters weren't here a moment ago?

180
00:09:11,350 --> 00:09:12,450
Surprise, right?

181
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:13,480
A miracle.

182
00:09:14,650 --> 00:09:15,050
Damn.

183
00:09:15,910 --> 00:09:17,330
Is something else falling out of your hair?

184
00:09:17,530 --> 00:09:18,270
That's dandruff.

185
00:09:18,430 --> 00:09:18,750
No.

186
00:09:21,050 --> 00:09:33,250
That's V. R. Behind the ear, U. And on the tongue?

187
00:09:33,760 --> 00:09:34,240
J.

188
00:09:37,150 --> 00:09:48,950
I'd rather not know where you've got the P hidden. Look, here we have RDEL.

189
00:09:49,340 --> 00:09:50,920
One word comes to mind.

190
00:09:51,120 --> 00:09:51,960
Mine too.

191
00:09:52,160 --> 00:09:54,200
Mine too, but it probably isn't in the dictionary.

192
00:09:54,240 --> 00:09:57,960
Well, if you're thinking of the same word as me, it is in the dictionary.

193
00:09:58,240 --> 00:09:59,380
Oh, how strange.

194
00:09:59,880 --> 00:10:02,420
Whenever I'm nervous, my whole body itches.

195
00:10:03,790 --> 00:10:04,490
And there it is.

196
00:10:04,790 --> 00:10:06,150
You should wash yourself sometimes.

197
00:10:09,580 --> 00:10:10,060
"Krdel"?

198
00:10:11,850 --> 00:10:13,650
I was expecting more of a vulgar word.

199
00:10:14,650 --> 00:10:16,250
Everyone has different taste.

200
00:10:18,650 --> 00:10:23,360
I'll check if it's in the dictionary, but I seriously doubt it.

201
00:10:25,250 --> 00:10:27,380
So that's your secret weapon, bro.

202
00:10:27,380 --> 00:10:28,280
We're screwed.

203
00:10:28,460 --> 00:10:29,120
"Krdel."

204
00:10:30,020 --> 00:10:31,620
Old Czech expression for abundance.

205
00:10:31,820 --> 00:10:33,660
You have 18 points.

206
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:37,510
And here I have a word.

207
00:10:39,420 --> 00:10:40,140
Delicacy.

208
00:10:40,140 --> 00:10:41,580
And that gives us 80...

209
00:10:41,580 --> 00:10:42,540
...

210
00:10:42,540 --> 00:10:44,100
60 points.

211
00:10:44,480 --> 00:10:45,440
I won.

212
00:10:45,950 --> 00:10:49,850
Say goodbye to the tickets.

213
00:10:50,950 --> 00:10:54,090
If we played a proper game, I'd wipe the floor with you.

214
00:10:54,090 --> 00:10:54,610
You think?

215
00:10:55,250 --> 00:10:56,650
Unless you're scared, that is.

216
00:10:58,090 --> 00:10:58,610
Never.

217
00:11:16,350 --> 00:11:18,550
Trump, trump, and seven to finish.

218
00:11:31,050 --> 00:11:33,550
I'd like to chop a brick in half with my bare hand.

219
00:11:34,150 --> 00:11:35,150
Want to see?

220
00:11:35,780 --> 00:11:36,020
No.

221
00:11:38,050 --> 00:11:40,050
Fine, so what do we play now?

222
00:11:40,550 --> 00:11:42,610
I remember one we used to play at school.

223
00:11:42,750 --> 00:11:43,950
Damn, how did it go.

224
00:11:44,050 --> 00:11:46,830
Hold on, I'm not playing spin the bottle.

225
00:11:46,830 --> 00:11:47,350
Yeah!

226
00:11:49,240 --> 00:11:50,600
Someone has to go behind the door.

227
00:11:50,780 --> 00:11:51,400
Yeah, I'll go.

228
00:11:51,500 --> 00:11:52,740
I'll go first, okay?

229
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:59,730
And then what?

230
00:12:00,630 --> 00:12:01,110
I don't know.

231
00:12:08,350 --> 00:12:09,550
This is getting ridiculous.

232
00:12:09,580 --> 00:12:11,220
We're so sorry, Marcelka.

233
00:12:11,220 --> 00:12:14,220
The door must have gotten jammed somehow yesterday.

234
00:12:14,220 --> 00:12:15,460
That's not what I'm talking about.

235
00:12:15,640 --> 00:12:16,680
Oh, then what?

236
00:12:17,750 --> 00:12:19,090
There won't be a concert.

237
00:12:19,090 --> 00:12:19,570
What?

238
00:12:20,950 --> 00:12:21,750
What do you mean there won't be?

239
00:12:22,250 --> 00:12:23,450
The Stones broke up?

240
00:12:23,950 --> 00:12:24,920
Richards fell apart.

241
00:12:25,050 --> 00:12:25,950
It's going to rain!

242
00:12:28,250 --> 00:12:31,010
The concert is still on, but the tickets are gone.

243
00:12:31,250 --> 00:12:32,450
Somebody stole them from me.

244
00:12:32,570 --> 00:12:33,090
Oh, I see.

245
00:12:33,910 --> 00:12:35,990
Why don't you just say right away that nothing happened?

246
00:12:36,190 --> 00:12:39,810
Wait, bro, you think it's fine that someone stole Marcelka's tickets?

247
00:12:41,550 --> 00:12:42,720
Yeah, she wouldn't have given them to us anyway.

248
00:12:43,050 --> 00:12:44,550
I just don't understand it.

249
00:12:44,950 --> 00:12:46,880
Alright, and when did you last see them?

250
00:12:47,050 --> 00:12:48,050
At your place.

251
00:12:48,850 --> 00:12:50,450
And what are you trying to say by that?

252
00:12:51,650 --> 00:12:54,340
Nothing, just where I last saw them.

253
00:12:54,550 --> 00:12:55,050
Well, that sounded pretty suspicious.

254
00:12:57,800 --> 00:13:00,300
It sounded like "you stole my tickets."

255
00:13:01,020 --> 00:13:03,180
I'm sorry, I didn't mean it that way.

256
00:13:03,320 --> 00:13:08,220
But I was standing behind that door for so long, and then you were throwing my things out the window...

257
00:13:08,220 --> 00:13:09,560
Well, there was no other way.

258
00:13:10,220 --> 00:13:12,020
I just don't know where I put them.

259
00:13:12,220 --> 00:13:18,380
You simply lost them, but the first thing you say is Ozzak stole my tickets.

260
00:13:18,950 --> 00:13:24,150
No, Ozzak, I didn't mean to say that and I'm sorry you took it that way.

261
00:13:24,450 --> 00:13:30,750
Fine, I'll take it as a momentary lapse of sanity, because if something like that happened to me...

262
00:13:31,050 --> 00:13:33,750
I'd go next door to the closet and hang myself.

263
00:13:35,150 --> 00:13:37,150
I'm not taking it that hard.

264
00:13:39,330 --> 00:13:39,890
Too bad.

265
00:13:49,350 --> 00:14:25,900
Remind me how it goes... So, Tomas, I'm ordering that young Mondrakova and we're crossing that Nohavica off the list.

266
00:14:25,900 --> 00:14:27,160
How could you do this to me?

267
00:14:28,550 --> 00:14:29,550
Bro, not waking you up when you oversleep is a family tradition.

268
00:14:29,750 --> 00:14:36,950
How could you hide those tickets when you know full well what they mean to me?

269
00:14:37,550 --> 00:14:39,200
Maybe you should go lie down.

270
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:41,120
You shouldn't be selling in this state.

271
00:14:41,620 --> 00:14:42,620
Marcelka is right.

272
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:43,360
Oh really!

273
00:14:44,080 --> 00:14:46,160
So you've all conspired against me, huh?

274
00:14:46,880 --> 00:14:50,320
You stole my tickets and now you're playing dumb, pretending you know nothing?

275
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:51,940
What tickets?

276
00:14:52,380 --> 00:14:53,100
Ozzak.

277
00:14:53,180 --> 00:14:55,760
It was me who lost tickets to Rolling Stones.

278
00:14:55,760 --> 00:14:57,320
I'm talking about my tickets!

279
00:14:57,850 --> 00:15:00,200
And where did you get tickets to Rolling Stones?

280
00:15:00,200 --> 00:15:00,920
I can't say!

281
00:15:02,550 --> 00:15:04,250
I'd endanger someone close to me.

282
00:15:07,750 --> 00:15:10,640
You stole Marcelka's tickets.

283
00:15:10,850 --> 00:15:12,440
There's theft and then there's theft.

284
00:15:12,440 --> 00:15:14,100
This theft was justified.

285
00:15:14,340 --> 00:15:14,860
What?

286
00:15:15,100 --> 00:15:22,100
Sure, for her they're just three slips of paper she'll wrap us around her finger with, but for me, for me, bro, for me they're tickets to heaven.

287
00:15:22,160 --> 00:15:23,200
To hell, actually.

288
00:15:23,460 --> 00:15:24,500
To the cauldrons.

289
00:15:24,880 --> 00:15:27,060
I hope you burn there alive.

290
00:15:31,750 --> 00:15:35,450
So you hadn't hidden my tickets.

291
00:15:37,250 --> 00:15:40,450
On top of that, we've lost someone who worked here.

292
00:15:41,390 --> 00:15:42,810
That would suit you, wouldn't it?

293
00:15:43,450 --> 00:15:45,110
So what am I supposed to do now?

294
00:15:47,750 --> 00:15:50,050
The rope is in the closet.

295
00:15:55,950 --> 00:15:58,670
Whatever, we'll see from home.

296
00:15:58,670 --> 00:16:00,690
Your old man can't possibly be bothered by this.

297
00:16:04,050 --> 00:16:06,050
Life is so unfair.

298
00:16:06,320 --> 00:16:09,180
This is exactly how Rolling Stones sound from a can.

299
00:16:09,200 --> 00:16:15,960
And anyone who has archaeological tendencies like me and wants to hear them live should prick up their ears now.

300
00:16:16,040 --> 00:16:19,240
The contest for tickets to tomorrow's concert continues.

301
00:16:19,380 --> 00:16:22,440
Only for die-hard fans of the rolling boulders.

302
00:16:22,640 --> 00:16:25,240
Call five sevens and two twos.

303
00:16:26,580 --> 00:16:36,730
And we have our first contestant.

304
00:16:36,730 --> 00:16:41,210
I hope you're a die-hard Stones fan, because otherwise you'll get zilch, not tickets.

305
00:16:41,210 --> 00:16:42,610
What's your name, buddy?

306
00:16:43,450 --> 00:16:44,460
Ozzak!

307
00:16:44,650 --> 00:16:48,060
Sit tight, cowboy, because this is gonna be rough.

308
00:16:48,060 --> 00:16:48,980
The question is.

309
00:16:49,280 --> 00:16:53,040
What large animals were discovered in Congo in 1901?

310
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:56,840
A: okapis, B: pipes, or C: sheet metal.

311
00:16:56,920 --> 00:16:57,900
Answer immediately.

312
00:16:58,180 --> 00:17:00,220
Can I phone a plumber friend?

313
00:17:00,540 --> 00:17:01,800
Okapis, pipes, sheet metal.

314
00:17:01,880 --> 00:17:02,500
Quickly now.

315
00:17:03,350 --> 00:17:04,350
Well come on, quickly.

316
00:17:04,430 --> 00:17:06,150
But they're okapis!

317
00:17:06,650 --> 00:17:07,850
You blew it, cowboy.

318
00:17:08,250 --> 00:17:10,550
A doofus like you wouldn't enjoy the concert anyway.

319
00:17:10,610 --> 00:17:15,490
Take care, and the rest of us will be competing for Rolling Stones tickets again tomorrow at this time.

320
00:17:15,690 --> 00:17:16,070
Again.

321
00:17:16,330 --> 00:17:20,790
Don't worry about it, bro.

322
00:17:20,910 --> 00:17:22,290
It was too complicated.

323
00:17:22,410 --> 00:17:24,150
Well, I've been listening since this morning.

324
00:17:24,270 --> 00:17:26,370
Of today's doofuses, you were the best.

325
00:17:26,590 --> 00:17:29,270
That guy just doesn't want to let anyone win.

326
00:17:29,710 --> 00:17:30,490
Like Mamba.

327
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:35,150
But Marcelka could handle him.

328
00:17:46,550 --> 00:17:50,790
I can feel it in my bones that today luck will finally smile on someone.

329
00:17:50,790 --> 00:17:53,490
Our first contestant has already gotten through.

330
00:17:54,190 --> 00:17:55,110
Good afternoon.

331
00:17:56,150 --> 00:18:00,410
Alright, listen up, sweetie, stick out your tongue and tell me what's correct.

332
00:18:00,650 --> 00:18:08,730
Alfred Nobel got a patent for: A, dynamite, B, common sense, or C, a sewing machine.

333
00:18:09,350 --> 00:18:10,630
Dynamite.

334
00:18:10,750 --> 00:18:11,610
Dynamite.

335
00:18:11,610 --> 00:18:12,110
I think.

336
00:18:13,350 --> 00:18:14,550
That's tough.

337
00:18:14,680 --> 00:18:16,960
Nobel invented the sewing machine, didn't he?

338
00:18:17,220 --> 00:18:19,700
Only primitives call in to these contests.

339
00:18:19,800 --> 00:18:23,760
Sorry, babe, but the correct answer is A, dynamite.

340
00:18:24,150 --> 00:18:28,740
After the song, we'll compete for tickets once more, and this time for the last time.

341
00:18:29,150 --> 00:18:32,850
These radio contests just have no standards anymore.

342
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:35,880
What if we said?

343
00:18:36,550 --> 00:18:37,650
Maybe, kid.

344
00:18:38,250 --> 00:18:40,950
When a woman says no, she always means yes.

345
00:18:41,450 --> 00:18:45,950
And when she says maybe, she's getting ready to say no, which means she's really saying yes.

346
00:18:47,350 --> 00:18:51,550
Wait, bro, is there any possibility that a woman actually means no?

347
00:18:52,230 --> 00:18:52,770
No.

348
00:18:53,250 --> 00:18:54,450
Man.

349
00:18:55,150 --> 00:18:56,550
I have to go see Iva.

350
00:18:57,750 --> 00:18:59,250
Go through Mamba.

351
00:19:02,450 --> 00:19:03,250
Marcelka, you look really great today.

352
00:19:05,210 --> 00:19:06,550
Just like Angelina Jolie.

353
00:19:07,090 --> 00:19:09,290
Full lips and an athletic body.

354
00:19:09,450 --> 00:19:12,490
And you look best when you're calling in to the contest.

355
00:19:14,350 --> 00:19:16,210
Pack your bags, little boy.

356
00:19:16,450 --> 00:19:17,730
You won't talk me into it.

357
00:19:18,750 --> 00:19:19,860
And zip up your fly.

358
00:19:19,860 --> 00:19:21,980
Or at least put on some underwear.

359
00:19:26,750 --> 00:19:32,450
I'm telling you, she'll be begging to call in to the radio.

360
00:19:33,550 --> 00:19:34,280
Watch me.

361
00:19:34,280 --> 00:19:39,720
Excuse me.

362
00:19:41,160 --> 00:19:41,780
Please.

363
00:20:00,250 --> 00:20:03,650
Well, I just got really angry, let me tell you.

364
00:20:08,450 --> 00:20:09,950
I have my reasons.

365
00:20:10,450 --> 00:20:11,490
Well, no.

366
00:20:12,350 --> 00:20:15,650
Don't take this personally, Marcelka, but that contest is out of your league.

367
00:20:17,470 --> 00:20:18,130
What?

368
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:22,710
I'm saying that you're not cut out for that radio contest.

369
00:20:22,710 --> 00:20:26,330
We can easily handle such a dimwitted little contest.

370
00:20:26,570 --> 00:20:31,010
Look, a lot of people listen to the radio, and if you got it wrong...

371
00:20:31,010 --> 00:20:35,150
Tomas, you know very well that I basically never get anything wrong.

372
00:20:35,370 --> 00:20:37,530
Wait, you actually want to win the contest?

373
00:20:38,530 --> 00:20:39,190
Of course.

374
00:20:40,540 --> 00:20:42,100
I'd like to see that.

375
00:20:42,220 --> 00:20:43,700
Me too.

376
00:20:43,700 --> 00:20:44,620
Me too.

377
00:20:47,350 --> 00:20:50,030
Then give me the number and get out of the shop.

378
00:20:50,150 --> 00:20:51,150
Five.

379
00:20:55,850 --> 00:21:00,650
Give me the phone number for the radio and leave me alone.

380
00:21:05,350 --> 00:21:10,060
And we're starting the final round of the contest for tickets to the concert of the decade.

381
00:21:10,060 --> 00:21:12,820
The concert starts in less than three hours.

382
00:21:13,230 --> 00:21:15,050
And who's gotten through to us?

383
00:21:15,250 --> 00:21:16,950
Good afternoon, this is Marcela from Prague.

384
00:21:17,170 --> 00:21:18,450
A fangirl called Marcelka.

385
00:21:18,790 --> 00:21:20,670
So how old are you, kitten?

386
00:21:21,710 --> 00:21:24,890
Kindly keep your sexist remarks to yourself and get started already.

387
00:21:25,070 --> 00:21:26,230
I don't have that much time.

388
00:21:26,650 --> 00:21:29,030
Oh, so the kitty is showing her claws.

389
00:21:29,750 --> 00:21:32,530
For that, you'll get no hints.

390
00:21:32,530 --> 00:21:33,610
Let's get to it then.

391
00:21:34,550 --> 00:21:37,250
Who first proposed a steam engine?

392
00:21:37,250 --> 00:21:37,790
Stevenson?

393
00:21:38,050 --> 00:21:38,590
Papin?

394
00:21:39,490 --> 00:21:41,310
Hero of Alexandria, in Egypt.

395
00:21:41,390 --> 00:21:42,290
Around the year 100.

396
00:21:43,350 --> 00:21:44,700
Excellent.

397
00:21:44,850 --> 00:21:46,940
Moving on.

398
00:21:47,350 --> 00:21:50,860
When did the day start being divided into 24 hours?

399
00:21:50,860 --> 00:21:52,720
The day has 24 hours?

400
00:21:52,720 --> 00:21:58,120
About three thousand years BC, in Mesopotamia.

401
00:21:58,120 --> 00:21:59,680
Even better, girl.

402
00:22:01,450 --> 00:22:03,400
And the last question.

403
00:22:04,050 --> 00:22:07,650
What was invented in China in the year 696?

404
00:22:08,090 --> 00:22:09,090
Porcelain?

405
00:22:10,490 --> 00:22:13,570
Mechanical clocks, and they were driven by a waterwheel.

406
00:22:13,970 --> 00:22:15,850
Brilliant for the third time.

407
00:22:16,070 --> 00:22:18,250
Well, you're really top class.

408
00:22:18,750 --> 00:22:22,370
So I've got three Rolling Stones tickets for you.

409
00:22:22,370 --> 00:22:31,920
Sing something by them to prove you're a real fan.

410
00:22:32,260 --> 00:22:33,140
But I...

411
00:22:33,140 --> 00:22:43,950
I've got some kind of vocal cord problem right now, so it would be better without the singing.

412
00:22:44,040 --> 00:22:45,080
The rules are clear.

413
00:22:45,080 --> 00:22:47,950
No singing, no tickets, kitty cat.

414
00:22:49,450 --> 00:22:51,450
Well then, fine.

415
00:23:02,550 --> 00:23:12,550
Alright, I won't torture you anymore.

416
00:23:15,390 --> 00:23:18,370
The contest was for Stones fans and that you definitely aren't.

417
00:23:20,050 --> 00:23:21,550
After her, to the shop.

418
00:23:31,820 --> 00:23:32,300
Come on!

419
00:23:32,420 --> 00:23:39,790
What happened?

420
00:23:40,050 --> 00:23:41,250
Marcelka couldn't sing.

421
00:23:41,270 --> 00:23:42,450
She was in a tough spot.

422
00:23:42,570 --> 00:23:44,330
Stop being stupid and give first aid.

423
00:23:44,890 --> 00:23:45,370
Sparkling water.

424
00:23:48,650 --> 00:23:50,850
Wait, I'll get some water.

425
00:23:56,250 --> 00:23:57,550
Tomas, I didn't win.

426
00:24:00,110 --> 00:24:05,130
It happens, Marcelka, worse things happen in life, right?

427
00:24:05,310 --> 00:24:06,130
What worse things?

428
00:24:06,290 --> 00:24:07,910
For me, life ends today.

429
00:24:08,650 --> 00:24:10,750
I'll go to the hairdresser, buy new clothes, and wash myself for him.

430
00:24:13,360 --> 00:24:17,740
Easy, easy, easy, Marcelka, it's alright, calm down, everything will be fine.

431
00:24:24,450 --> 00:24:26,250
Thank you, Tomas, but could you let go of my hands? I'm lying on something and it's really poking me in the ribs.

432
00:24:29,950 --> 00:24:35,030
Oh my God, these are my tickets.

433
00:24:35,350 --> 00:24:36,250
What time is it?

434
00:24:36,250 --> 00:24:37,030
Fourteen hundred hours.

435
00:24:37,330 --> 00:24:39,010
Exactly, nineteen hours, seventeen minutes.

436
00:24:39,370 --> 00:24:41,510
Then we'd better hurry if we want to make it.

437
00:24:42,450 --> 00:24:43,150
Tomas.

438
00:24:43,250 --> 00:24:43,810
Thank you.

439
00:24:44,010 --> 00:24:44,230
Lexa.

440
00:24:44,370 --> 00:24:45,270
Thank you, Mrs. Marcelka.

441
00:24:50,110 --> 00:24:50,590
Ozzak.

442
00:24:50,590 --> 00:24:51,070
Thanks.

443
00:24:52,390 --> 00:24:53,750
You don't have to thank me, Ozzak.

444
00:24:53,750 --> 00:25:00,850
I'm not giving you this ticket because I feel something for you, but because the music means nothing to me.

445
00:25:00,850 --> 00:25:04,160
And I only carried you here so you wouldn't be lying on the shop floor.

446
00:25:04,580 --> 00:25:05,840
A draw, huh?

447
00:25:05,900 --> 00:25:06,320
You bet!

448
00:25:14,250 --> 00:25:16,650
Marcelka, do you have a moment?

449
00:25:17,050 --> 00:25:17,750
Of course.

450
00:25:18,250 --> 00:25:19,450
Is something going on?

451
00:25:20,650 --> 00:25:22,150
Would you like to play Scrabble?

452
00:25:23,730 --> 00:25:24,610
I'd love to.

453
00:25:29,450 --> 00:25:35,030
I can get no satisfaction.

454
00:25:35,030 --> 00:25:40,470
I can get no satisfaction.

455
00:25:46,850 --> 00:25:54,050
That's good, I know that guy from somewhere, what is it.
